{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608028"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0.55,0.18,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8667"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8597"},{"type":"tags","id":"8599"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the second week of human embryonic development, the inner cell mass splits into two distinct cell layers. One layer will form the placenta and extraembryonic membranes, while the other will develop into the embryo proper.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures gives rise to all three primary germ layers of the embryo?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trophoblast","Hypoblast","Epiblast","Primitive streak","Cytotrophoblast"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiblast\u003C/strong\u003E is the dorsal layer of the bilaminar disc that forms all three germ layers (endoderm, mesoderm, and ectoderm) during gastrulation through cellular migration and differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E makes up the outer layer of the blastocyst and develops into bits of the placenta\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoblast\u003C/strong\u003E makes up the ventral layer of the bilaminar disc and forms the yolk sac\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimitive streak\u003C/strong\u003E pops up later and acts as the spot where epiblast cells move through during gastrulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytotrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E is the inner layer of trophoblast cells that helps build the placenta\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnly the epiblast can form all embryonic tissues. The other structures just contribute to extraembryonic bits like the placenta and yolk sac.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The epiblast forms from the inner cell mass and gives rise to all three germ layers during gastrulation.","The epiblast sits on the dorsal side of the bilaminar disc, next to the amniotic cavity.","The hypoblast and trophoblast only form extraembryonic structures, not the embryo proper."],"references":["Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61347","links":{"self":"https://